History of IBM: from cheese cutter to space flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was already adopted in 1924 - originally it was a brand used at the branches of Canada and South America.
The basis for the birth of IBM emerged from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He had inventions like the famous "fix clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired his supervisory board until 1930.
Flint put the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson's ideas remain the firm basis on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat cutters and cheese to register boxes.
During the first four years of Watson’s management of the company, the billing doubled by $9 million and began the large expansion of the company across the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, almost forty years after occupying the boss's chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which established the computer standard of that time, came to the market with the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer complete advice and services of high added value.
