How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies of that time sold in most cases travel only to the socialist bloc, as the trips to the West were very restricted.
The Czech tourists therefore went on vacation to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, after that the Yugoslav regime was inclined west and the journeys of Czech tourists were then rather restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., also the Slovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually, not even by the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West in those days, but one had to go to the queue with a sleeping bag and spend all night, or have "good-known" in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" which was the condition for trips to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable agent", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This habit still persists.
The way Czechs travel has suffered a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was the no longer going to spend holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that Croatia, until 1989, was unable to travel freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, the visa exemption was imposed to travel to Western European neighbouring States, resulting in a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czech-Slovaks, for a long time, didn't see enough of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in parks in tents, since our incomes at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to carry with them the food (conservatives, stuffed, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the conversionability of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy western currency.
Our standard of living was increasing and with it average wages, which led to an increase in travel demand around 1997.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began to prepare trips on a regular basis from 1997 onwards using charter flight connections, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for passenger volumes.
By the end of the 90th century, Czechs were already travelling visa-free to almost all developed countries, except the US, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism occurred in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Chechnya to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have started every year, making countries far away and warm. This winter will be flying directly from Czechia to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries are currently visiting around 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, so our country became one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have been spent on trips abroad more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head, including expenses on the stay site.
