7 Lessons of Steve Jobs' Lost Interview, are shown in a theater this week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius of technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans could find more revealing, in an interview with recently rediscovered Jobs that has been dusted out as a step forward of a series of special projections in the biggest markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the commercial processes and workflows of products.
He was undoubtedly a self-recognizable designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a youngki of flow diagrams - a man who believed that many executives suffered "a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the TV series The Triumph of the Nerds on the debut of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At that time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively in his new NeXT computer company, awaiting popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs died that a complete copy of VHS was discovered in the manager's garage.
This slightly republished archive material is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview that arrives at the Landmark cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate deep interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
In four different points during the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, where it seems impatient because of Cringely's questions, pushing him to go faster to the subjects or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the Pixar era, the iPod or the iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what other companies see doing right and wrong, and offers their own vision of the future of computer science.
One thing is to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs' career, but there is something raw and inspiring in the Jobs we see here, the dreamer anxiously at the edge of greatness.
He has a vision of how they can and must be things.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to take a business:
"Over the years in the business, I always asked, "Why do you do things?" and the answers they give you invariably are, "Oh, that's just the way it's done."
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs leads to detail his efforts to simplify Apple's accounting.
Disagreed by the way in which the costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was made to the eye of good copper, and then adjusted to a "variable" - developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine the commercial costs in detail.
About the joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" that he himself built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to hack effectively the telephone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been written widely about the device, but Jobs' euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
Describes how he and Wozniak tried the box by using a public phone, making one call, and then connecting from one AT & T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were getting things all around the world half a dozen times and screaming through the public phone and returning a minute later to the public phone next door," Jobs says with a laugh.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world."
The two of us, we didn't know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing -- it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think it ever existed without Apple.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak to the Pope while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two burst into carcasses just before the Pope himself was awakened to answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling by phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the telephone guide and called him.
Shortly after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job in Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and formed my vision of what was a company and how well they treated their employees."
Jobs later became one of HP employees who visited the company's research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first table computer ever made".
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a little cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste my time with that machine and write programs for her.
About improvising innovation:
At several points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the march.
Soon in his career, as he was dedicated to selling a handful of base plates, a customer asked him if he could mount the entire equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to find out how the finished devices were assembled and delivered.
Later, while in Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in the development of a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments... they shouted at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got mad and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On large companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple's rebirth, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble into his vision, and lose control of his market share.
"Say you work in IBM or Xerox, so you make photocopiers and printers better, so what?"
You have the monopoly of the market share, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so these kinds of people who end up running companies and people in charge of products are expelled from the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to this monopoly position is rotten because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened in Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 1990s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows."
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to do - some things you can't do that make electrons, the glass makes them, the robots make them, the factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
At the end, everything is reduced to taste - it goes down to trying to expose you to the best that a human team has done, and then try to adapt those things to which you are doing.
Picasso said good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed of stealing big ideas.
What partly made Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who were by chance the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for computer science, it could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
