How to Detect a Lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and omnipresent deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment charges with several women; each party charges lying to the other.
The administrators of the State University of Pennsylvania have been accused of perjury for allegedly concealing reports that said a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolás Sarkozy was "traped" with an open-label microphone telling U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and seizures countries.
Congressman for New York and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made the ridicule with his dissidents quickly refuted by the irrefutable test.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of infringing the funding of the campaign related to the covering of an extramarital relationship.
And again, no one who lives will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about the traps are widely spread in school and university exams.
There have been cases where teachers have given the answers of the exams to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lies and deception are acceptable.
How deceptive are we?
On any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that the unknown lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies", is an essential skill that we must all acquire for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a table game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to say: "I have you," the detection of deception is a branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the last six decades at prestigious universities that carried out research projects in depth, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about the lie have been refuted.
Liars do look in the eyes.
They don't always stutter, bluff, rub or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or expose.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, the microfaced expressions, the formation of questions and times.
I spent several years investigating scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate through our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include recruitment, interviews, or negotiation management.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions and feeling intuitively how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented minds," while women say more "oriented-to-other" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less frequently to their mates than those who are not married (but the lies they usually say tend to be "great").
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty when you lie to him.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject’s usual behavior.
This is called "creating a baseline."
Helps to provide benchmarks to measure later changes.
Observe the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristic.
It is better to know if someone usually hits his foot all the time to avoid making unfair accusations when he sees his feet beating in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for misleading, verbal and non-verbal behavior groups.
Consider these behavior groups as alarm signals, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the upper part of the body by trying to remember their story, can point their feet towards the door, lean towards a exit, change their posture significantly or exhibit a "post-interview shock" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of position once all difficult questions have ended.
The interrogators often falsely point out that the interview ended only to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson kicked his foot to the bottom and used the past time while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a search for her at the national level.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when he answers a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... until I... understand."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
