Climate Adversity curbed the economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, Sinaloa has increased unemployment and informality, lowered foreign investment and contracted the economy
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-denominated of change, who generated great expectations for progress in the economy, but given the early climate adversity of the year, growth is not observed, but there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
Low temperatures in February, in addition to causing millions of losses to the agricultural sector, limited the opportunities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of the overall economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historical fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of ice cream allocations issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there were damage in 582,000 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 per cent had partial damage, the main damaged crops were vegetables, maize and garbanzo.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of state unemployment during the first three quarters of the year was seen an accelerated growth, as while January to March 55 thousand 053 signal citizens were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the economically active population, by the second quarter the rate increased to 5.28 per cent, and between July and September the average continued to rise to 6.19 per cent, a rate that in number of unemployed people to more than 74 thousand signals, an increase over the first half of 18 thousand 969 individuals.
Less Liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have taken place since public policy.
"What is being seen is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity on the market for the effects of a resource restriction by the legislation adopted at the congress to combat money laundering, and for people who take dollars illegally, it is not easy for them to work, invest and use them in something," he said.
Organisation
López Cervantes noted that there is also a demographic factor in rising unemployment.
"The number of people who leave the state looking for work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties to enter, and second because they already have many difficulties to find work, these people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which makes unemployment rise," he said.
Informality
The analysis of the labour market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality prevailing among working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in the state works without being contributing as a worker to any social security institution.
Together with unemployment and informality, another of the state's labour wages is low wages, the entity has the lowest remuneration in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Security.
The average monthly income of signanese workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7,000 375 pesos.
FDI Contraction
Together with the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 the highest decrease in Direct Foreign Investment in the last 10 years was recorded, according to the State FDI Secretariat from January to June, amounting to $630,697, representing a fall of 87,74 per cent compared to the $5 million 143,000,312 recorded during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the State Government's Economic Development Secretariat accounts for a total investment of 17 000 280 million pesos per year, mainly from third-party companies.
The debt
In the context of the economic contraction scenario, the Government of the State requested in July the state congress to approve a 3 billion pesos credit, even though investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, in order to reactivate the economy, the approval of the local congress was for a total of 2 billion pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For business sector representatives, the first year of Government of Mario López Valdés shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 he failed to harmonize the will of the various sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we must work hard to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, failed to align the effort of all and above all the good progress already synchronized of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López stated that events such as early-year ice cream stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"Low economic flow is the result of several events, including ice cream, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn back fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services, and so at the end of the year we are closing much below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, stated that it is necessary to lead the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have been working, we believe it is necessary to develop a long-term programme in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has," he said.
Work to be done
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that best guides the efforts of the Government.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has been trying to achieve good results in various areas, there are some progress in economic development, but it is important that a long-term programme be developed," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in driving public policy.
"There are elements to say that the Government is becoming more inclusive, I can say is that there is work done and I believe that the Government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
