Court valid "analog parrot" in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional disputes brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree advancing the so-called "analog blackout" from 2021 to 2015, not bringing together the eight votes necessary to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to implement the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional dispute promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft sentence, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a power reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and of reservation of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the House of Deputies promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the decree, and in admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions in it prepared for the digital transition.
The full ministers also decided to dismiss the request made by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also by Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the President said he did not match the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive could not structure measures to prepare the public administration through general rules.
"I also do not consider that if I did so, the autonomy of the regulatory body would be affected," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector corresponds to the federal executive, who is constitutionally mandated, the head of the State.
The substitution of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years, and it translates into a better use of the radio spectrum, a better quality of the signal and more channels.
To postpone the change would be to postpone the benefits of digitisation, which implies a decision of public interest, which does not have only a technical dimension, "then it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he pointed out, "require the operation of the whole established system, in accordance with the principle of economic leadership of the State, includes a group of powers which the Constitution leads to the power of the State executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and has done so through the executive, despite highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the executive, by issuing the contested decree, which somehow invades the sphere of competence of Congress, is being provided in the administrative field the observance of laws issued by the legislature, ensured.
They analyze the possibility of a voting vote count in Michoacán
According to the data provided by the PREP, the difference between the first and second place of the governor's election is only 27 per cent, although the votes for 879 of the total 6 thousand 74 minutes are not recorded.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality in terms of the electoral process of this year in Michoacán, where according to the data from the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the total 6 thousand 74 minutes.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, only on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
As you will recall, Michoacán did not approve its Political Constitution or its Electoral Code of the State or its Electoral Justice Act, provided that the Congress of the State passed the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for them to enter into force in the present electoral process, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted his publication within the time limits provided for in the State Official Journal Act, with the argument that he had some objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the Local Legislative Power and qualified the state representative's vote for constitutional reforms as "unvalid and illegal" as the vote of the state representative, provided he has no right to "sanitary or veto them".
Interviewed about the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Angeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the EMI it will be possible to make partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In such a way, the partial count of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be held on the assumption that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of the balloting and the record of the ballot or not open to the President of the ballot; or, where there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the vote received in all the voting boxes may be made when there is evidence that the difference between the alleged candidate who wins the election in question and the one who has obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is the express request from the representative of the party and/or coalition who postulated the second one of the candidates indicated.
The total count of the vote may also be made if at the end of the ordinary count it is established that the difference between the alleged winner candidate and the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is a express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate was second, in which case the electoral packages which have been partially counted will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that in this situation there is the choice of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and the second place is only 0.16 per cent, but without counting the votes of 129 of the total 923 minutes.
