MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Conducts Social Security research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; is supported by IDN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it conducts research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of Obesity of Children and Adolescents' protocol, which will enable markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital de Specialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of physicians, nurses, nurses and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvesav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (INP).
In the investigation, the population is invited to participate, whether or not right-to-be, to visit the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Mexico Valley, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico West) and that since 8 October, the activity is carried out at the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico East).
Once the objective of gathering 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
At the celebration of World Diabetes Day on 14 November, he stated that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14 with the consent and supervision of their parents for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and hereditary history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger diseases such as diabetes or renal failure.
He noted that on Saturdays all participants apply anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure intake, glucose levels determination, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (it is sought to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys noted that, in just six years, there was an increase of 77 percent in obesity among children and girls by 47 percent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic increase was also observed', the IMSS specialist said.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent of American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive evaluation of children, which allows them to detect whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) in the neck and forearm, indicating the probability of metabolic and even predisabetes alterations.
The information is handled in a confidential manner, the doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, who are explained to each of the measurements and changes in the lifestyle they need to make in order to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic suffering: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sugared beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid berries
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemicals, develops polymer modified asphalts to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the floor were met, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 berries each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt floor is the right one, the berries could be reduced in quantity or even completely eliminated.
At his conference A technological opinion of the berries, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory at its charge develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and therefore the formation of berries.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight ones, called asphalts, and others of low molecular weight, called malts, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, added.
The above means that asphalt resistance is not uniform in the streets, but is being modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher observed that most streets in Mexico City are covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the floor.
In the case of modified asphalt, the chemical engineer was of the opinion.
On the asphalt folder, abounded, a last layer called a treadmill is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with vehicle wheels, you should have more mechanical force than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the way.
Being the part of the floor that will receive and disseminate the efforts, the tread folder also needs to have the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made should be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil is wet, the water is diffused inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a replete of all layers of the floor and therefore the formation of berries.
In the process of forming a bach, he said, the first to wear out is the film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should meet the first signs with adequate maintenance programs.
