This was the work of the calenho that identified Alfonso Cano's body
A lophoscopist from Cali passed into history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
Last November 4th, a lophoscopist from the Cali ITC passed into history as the man who confirmed the identity of the chief of the Farc: "Alfonso Cano", through the stamp of his fingerprints.
Of the seven Lophoscopists working at the ITC section, that week was the turn of "availability" to Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the judicial investigation area for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to stay in the jungle for more than five days to get to the place where the corpses were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after performing the corresponding courses, he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is, the palms of his hands and feet.
The week of operation against Alfonso Cano alias to Elazar warned him to wear minimum clothes for three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for the Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being the man who was leading the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to carry Guillermo Leon Sáenz's cadactillary card (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the corpse was located, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance, because it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a peasant in the area, wearing glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
accompanied by a galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Elias compared the fingerprints of the body with those of the card.
His eye didn't fail: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for confirming the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinzón, who was the chief of the Farcs.
In search of the footprint
For a typtiloscopicist of the Sijín de Cali the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Elias González, in the press wheel for the operation against "Cano" is very significant.
Many people don't know our work.
Dictyloscopy is an accurate science, without margin of error, which can become a key in the resolution of crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, lophoscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many delinquents present false ballots or have no papers.
We take the fingerprint and we search them in the database.
The researcher reported that, in a case of theft, he was struck by removing a piece of wall from a house, for in that place the thief had supported his hand to pull out a strong box full of jewels and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to get a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the footprint of the entire hand and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts," he recalled.
The fingerprints may also rule out or reaffirm suspects in cases of murder.
Recently they found a dead man with bottles of liquor around him.
The investigation determined that a family member could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a trace in the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the killer, it does place him at the scene of the crime.
One ITC tyctyloscopeist explained that in the objects "the prints are taken with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said CTI expert.
He made it clear that not everything is as shown in the CSI television program.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that touches becomes trace.
However, if it can be used, if the respective knife is made.
