The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande is limited to including banalities, indicating that co-disarrollo will solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable electorally, but economically it comes out very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work that summarizes the most recent knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
The fears associated with the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, in particular those who are not qualified, with pressure to reduce their wages.
However, experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for national workers and primarily work in sectors with a lack of employment.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and those most qualified in dynamic sectors where training fails to meet staff demand.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country in need of anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to positively influence the wages and employment of nationals.
